1-INTRODUCTION

In this homework, a dataset named âMuskâ was given in which there are instances with bag IDs and their related features. The interesting thing about this dataset is that there are 92 bags containing more than 1 instances. Each bag is assigned to a class in a class set including binary classes 0 and 1. This dataset is an example of Multiple Instance Learning. In MIL, instance labels are not known. We only know the labels of bags. Labels are the class values.

Task

What is required for this homework is that we must summarize the instance level information to bag level information (i.e.Â there are 4 instances in first bag, how can I represent the first bag as a single feature vector). In addition, we have to follow certain steps to achieve this target.

Step 1

First step to complete the task is âCluster instances with some clustering algorithmâ In order to do that, I thought that I have to cluster the dataset in a way that each bag will become a cluster. Furthermore, after I cluster the dataset in that fashion, I should find the centroid of each of the clusters that is, bags.

At first I read the dataset in to R with âreadxlâ package and used âread.csvâ function. After I checked the structure of the dataset with âstrâ function, I realized that all of the columns are integer. I change the types of the first 2 columns which are Bag Class and Bag ID to factor with âas.factorâ function.

We are asked to propose two distance measures for computing similarity between the instances. For each distance measure alternative, we are expected to evaluate the performance of two clustering approaches: k-medoids and hierarchical clustering.

K-Medoids clustering

I started with clustering with k-medoids type. After I searched on the web, I learned that I need to use âpam (partitioning around medoids)â function from âclusterâ package. As a starting step, I scaled the dataset features, used k=92, metric = âeuclideanâ in pam function. Afterwads I used âcluster.statsâ function to evaluate the performance of my clustering algorithm with the parameters I selected. Later on, I repeated the same process with changing the metric to âmanhattanâ. In this way I became able to evaluate k-medoid clustering approach with two different distance measures, namely âeuclideanâ and âmanhattanâ.

There are metrics and functions to determine the best k value for pam clustering. As I explained above, since I should cluster the data set in a way that each bag becomes a cluster, I thought that k should be equal to number of the bags. Hence, I select the k value as 92 since there are 92 bags in the dataset.

Later, I tried to interpret the result of cluster.stats function for both of them. I learned from my searches that âdunnâ value is useful for comparing this two clustering approaches with different distance metrics. The higher the dunn value, the more prefereable the approach

Since k-medoid approach with euclidean distance is greater than k-medoid approach with manhattan distance, it is more appropriate to use.

You can see the results that I have explained below.

Hierarchical Clustering

After doing K-Medoids clustering, I did two hierarchical clusterings using euclidean and manhattan distance as well. Firstly, I calculate manhattan and euclidean distances with âdistâ function choosing method = âeuclideanâ and method = âmanhattan. Secondly, I usedâhclust" function with these different distance matrices and chose the method as âcentroid.â Later on I used âcutreeâ function to create 92 clusters and compare them with actual bags by merging them with âtableâ function. Again, I used âcluster.statsâ function for each of the clusters with euclidean and manhattan distances and extracted dunn values to compare their performance. The result is the same as K-medoids approach. The dunn value of hierarchical clustering approach with euclidean distance is greater than hierarchical clustering approach with manhattan distance, it is more preferable.

You can see the results that I have explained below.

COMPARING TWO APPROACHES

After I did K-medoids and Hierarchical clustering with euclidean and manhattan distance measures respectively, I compared them to determine the best approach with the best distance metric that I am going to continue with. In order to accomplish that I used âcluster.statsâ again but this time I evaluate the correctness of each of the approaches by comparing them with actual bags. After some detailed searching, I learned that I can use âcorrected.randâ value from results of cluster.stats to compare them. I did this four times. Two pam clusterings with euclidean and manhattan distance and two hierarchical clusterings with euclidean and manhattan distance. The higher the corrected.rand value, the more prefereable the approach. For this reason, K-Medoids clustering with euclidean distance is the best choice since its corrected rand value is the greatest among them.

## [1] 0.1490908
## [1] 0.1426598
## [1] 0.01086027
## [1] 0.01802536

stats_pam_euc$corrected.rand [1] 0.1490908

stats_pam_man$corrected.rand [1] 0.1426598

stats_h.fit_euc$corrected.rand [1] 0.01086027

stats_h.fit_man$corrected.rand [1] 0.01802536

Later, I tried to find the distances between medoids of each cluster and their corresponding points in that cluster. In order to do that, I used âpdistâ function.

I know that I did not follow a right path to reach the desired solution. Because the clusters that I have found with clustering algorithms are not the same as or close to the bags given. I tried to give different k values but what I understood from the homework sheet is that the number of the clusters should be equal to number of bags which is 92 and I should represent each bag as a cluster. Afterwards, I should find their centroids or in this case medoids and calculate the distances between medoids and the points of that cluster. As a last step, I should average this instance distances to the cluster centroids to represent a bag with a single distance. However, clustering algorithms did not give me clusters similar to these bags and the medoids I obtained are not consistent with bags centroids.

One of the things I thought is finding each bagâs mean and treat them as a cluster centroid to go further down the steps and complete the homework. However, I know that this would not be a clustering.

I searched on the web about Multiple Instance Learning and transforming instance-level information to bag-level representation. But I could not find a source that I can implement to this homework.

Therefore, I could not complete the second and hence, the third step. I am so sorry for that.

Thank you for your understanding.
